I live in Ontario, Canada, and our climate is similar to NYC’s, just a bit colder for a little linger but not much). Many people complain that the winters in these areas makes their skin dry but I get oilier in the winter. Maybe you’re experiencing the same thing I do. I think it’s because our winters can be quite cold and that means less moisture in the air. With less moisture, my skin becomes dehydrated and produces more oils to compensate. In the summer it’s the opposite for me. Summers here (and in New York) can be very humid and i find the extra water vapour helps my skin produce less oil. You likely have dehydrated skin like mine. Hydration is everything! Use more humectant ingredients like hyaluronic acid (which I’ve noticed is not as common in Korean skin care as skin care from North America or Europe) and glycerin, moisturizers that are water-based and cap it with a more occlusive products (at night, bit heavy for day time). Your skin will calm down. If I’m on a flight for more than a couple hours my skin goes crazy for a week or two…moving to a whole other continent is bound to make your skin react! Drink lots of water, add humectants to your skin care and either get a humidifier and place it near your bed or place a glass of water near a radiator for more moisture in your apartment. So glad you’re over this way learning English!! You’ll be soon speaking it beautifully, I’m sure!! :)
